        <td bgColor="black"><textarea cols="70" name="Message" rows="12" wrap="VIRTUAL">[quote]
This zone takes some getting used to.  I use a combination of fear-kiting, pet-tanking/slow/Vex/Shadowbond, and root-doting (or a combination of the above) depending on the situation.  The difficulty of the mobs will vary depending on what part of the zone you're in (as with many zones across Norath).

As was mentioned earlier, start near the Mons zone.  The area to the left of the zone along the wall is fairly safe and free of trains if no one else is pulling to that space as well.  The area at the base of the wall up to the hills near the corner is also a good spot for fear kiting.

Make sure you have DMF up in this zone.  It helps not only with enabling you to breathe, but helps with maneuvering around the boulders, etc.  I haven't confirmed this, but I suspect it may also help with seeing the white spots in the sand that mark the 'slug' traps.  You can actually see them moving around like little clouds which is kinda cool.  Walking over these will set them off.  If you have invis up, they will not attack, so don't get freaked out when you hear the trap pop.  The little boulder guys that have been alluded to are a pain.  They are traps that are attached to many of the rocks in the zone (they tend to congregate in the plains extending beyond the backside of the temple, but can be tripped elsewhere).  These little guys summon and are tough to take down solo, but can be rooted, feared, etc.  If you're soloing and run across them, FD and/or run to zone unless you have some support and/or a few more levels, experience fighting them, and plenty of health and mana.

Rockfiends are another hazard.  Best policy on these guys is to root them ASAP, get your pet away, then snare, then fear in this order.  They run at about J-Boot speed, so if you don't have snare on them and fear breaks, you're toast.  Other than that, they just have a ton of HP.  Fear kiting them seems to work best along with a healthy application of DOTs (keep that snare up).  To manage them so they don't get range too far, combine the fear kiting with some aggro-kiting to pull them back to a spot where you can re-apply fear.

After you get used to the space in the vicinity of Mons, I recommend moving steadily to the right of the zone along the wall.  You'll come across two small skelly ruins that are good areas to pull (keep an eye for the slug traps around these).

The slugs cannot be snared so the best policy on these is to send in the pet, keep him Shadowbonded and/or Pacted and then Vex/Bond/Deflux away.  It takes some mana, but can be done since they actually don't have a ton of HP.  If/when the pet starts to get low, move in and start tanking for your pet.  You'll be able to channel through the hits with deflux and should easily come out on top.

There are two ways to deal with skellies and/or snakes.  You can either do traditional root-doting and have the pet finish em off, or you can pull with slow, send in pet, fire off a shadowbond/pact, vex/bond, perhaps another DOT or DD and enjoy the show.  Fear as desired or as pet starts to get low.  You'll find that these guys are the standard fare and will get pretty efficient at killing them with some practice.  Golems are pretty easy too - easily snared, rooted, feared, etc. - not too many hp - they're the cattle of the Grey, just waitin fer slaughter :)

As you move around from the ruins, rotating to the right around the zone, you'll find the mobs start getting a little tougher.  The mobs at the Scarlet Desert side are better exp, but there also are more dangerous concentrations of them that can trip you up if you're not careful.

Stay away from the Undying Iksar unless you have a competent plus 55 couple of people with a lvl 60 puller who knows what they're doing (these can be Tag-pulled best)  They don't see invis, but are surrounded by slugs, rockfiends, and boulderings, and are linked very tightly together.  If you see a train of these lovely skellies heading you're way, run unless you have a good group and it's only a few (/chuckle - it's rare for Undying to come in trains of less than 5-10).

The temple can actually be great soloing and group exp.  To get to know it, I'd recommend starting with groups.  The best way to handle it is to keep the pulls fast and furious.  You're best friend here is your Root line of spells.  Dooming - Enstil - Undead Slow - Splurt - Fear are all mainstays.  Keep the pulls coming, focus the tanks on one mob at a time and root/snare/slow/splurt the rest.  This can be some seriously entertaining fun with a good group :) - with the benefit of an occasional named that can drop some goodies.  When fighting at the front, don't sit in the depression area (that's frequented by the slugs roaming back and forth).  The best spot to sit is on the edge of the depression between the snake ruins and the golems.  ALWAYS keep your eyes and ears open for trains here.  It's common for Temple Raids to have uninvissed tanks running to the zone with plenty of Rockfiends and big skellies in tow.  I swear it seems sometimes that they troll around the zone a while making sure they have enough before trucking through your camp (heh).  Even so, this is an excellent spot and you can even control the trains with some experience and people working together.

One last thing, I might add that this is a good zone to learn to use the terrain to your advantage.  When you have aggro, train mobs across all the big features.  Run across deep valleys, etc. and you will gain some valuable distance.


Hope this helps :)



Takilth Shadowpath
aka Necrotart
Iksar Warlock of the Final Shedding
proud member of Shining Alliance
Prexus

